description: From Middle English misleden, from Old English mislǣdan (“to mislead”), from Proto-Germanic *missalaidijaną (“to mislead”), equivalent to mis- +‎ lead.

entries.meaning: A wrong or bad lead; a leading in the wrong direction.
(countable) That which is deceptive or untruthful (e.g. a falsehood, deception, untruth, or ruse).

verbs.description: mislead (third-person singular simple present misleads, present participle misleading, simple past and past participle misled) (transitive)

entries.meaning: (literally) To lead astray, in a false direction.
To deceive by telling lies or otherwise giving a false impression.
To deceptively trick into something wrong.
examples: The preacher elaborated Satan's ways to mislead us into sin
